        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The HD(1-0) line flux of can be estimated using:

F_line = [N(HD) * A_10 * h * v * f_v]/(4 * pi * D^2), 

where N(HD) is the number of HD molecules in the beam, A_10 (= 5.44e-8 s-1) is the Einstein coefficient of the J=1-0 transition, h is the Planck constant, v = 2.674986094 THz is the rest frequency, D is the distance and 

f_v = 3 * exp(-128./T)/Q(T),

where 3 is the degeneracy of the J=1 level and Q(T) is the partition function. We assumed a gas temperature of T ~ 150 K (based on the observations of highly excited CO rotational transitions, Weiss et al. 2013), Q(T) = 2.7 (see JPL catalogue). 

From the intrinsic mass estimate of SPT0346-52 (1.48e10 M_sun), an HD/H2 ratio of 3e-5 (assuming a cosmic abundance of deuterium equal to 1.5e-5, e.g. Oliveira et al. 2003), the HD(1-0) line flux, after taking into account the lensing, is 8.5e-18 erg s-1 cm-2, which correspond to 1.5 mJy, assuming a line width of 700 km/s. 

From here, the line can be detected with S/N &gt; 7 sigma if an rms of 0.2 mJy is calculated over a band of 700 km/s. This can be achieved with an on-source integration time of only 50 minutes. With the same sensitivity we will achieve a S/N ~ 4 per spectral channel of 150 km/s, which is enough to also study the velocity profile of the line (although this is not the primary goal of the proposal). A simulation of the ALMA observation with an integration time of 50 minutes is shown in Figure 2. 

Two basebands (1 and 2) have been joined together to allow detection of the broad feature. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
